  <div class="homepage__spacer"></div>
  
  <div id="dont-get-too-caught-up" class="slide">
    <%= render_partial "h2-link.html", 
      link: "/guides/strategy-limitations#dont-get-too-caught-up", 
      title: "Don't Get Too Caught Up" 
    %>

    <p>The general idea behind mental health strategies is to help you organise and frame your problems in a way that's manageable.</p>
    <p>The reason this is problematic is because there is technically nothing wrong with you.</p>
    <p>However when you frame a problem in certain terms, you can end up creating a paradigm where it makes sense to address and create new problems, than it is to actually live without them.</p>
    <p>I suppose there's a fine line in terms of providing help. It needs to be accessible so that you're still working from the point of view of the patient and their perception of themselves.</p>
    <p>However, </p>
  </div>

  <div class="homepage__spacer"></div>
  
  <div id="what-it-doesnt-do" class="slide">
    <%= render_partial "h2-link.html", 
      link: "/guides/strategy-limitations#what-it-doesnt-do", 
      title: "What It Doesn't Do" 
    %>

    <p>What functioning mental health essentially buys you is additional control over your time.</p>
    <p>What this strategy cannot help you with is tell you what you should do with your time.</p>
    <p>It is not designed to help you structure your goals and ambitions.</p>
    <p>It's merely designed to help you become aware of your weakness.</p>
    <p>How you choose to proceed is entirely up to you.</p>
    <p>Don't expect self-awareness to radically give you the answers to everything in life.</p>
    <p>It simply provides you with a clear mind to make that decision.</p>
  </div>
</div>